SIMPLE: waver
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Waver
<hw>Wa"ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wavered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wavering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>waveren</ets>, from
AS. <ets>w⟦ae⟧fre</ets> wavering, restless. See <er>Wave</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To play or move to and fro; to move one way and the
other; hence, to totter; to reel; to swing; to flutter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With banners and pennons <qex>wavering</qex> with the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Ld. Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou wouldst <qex>waver</qex> on one of these trees as a terror to
all evil speakers against dignities.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be unsettled in opinion; to vacillate; to be
undetermined; to fluctuate; <as>as, to <ex>water</ex> in
judgment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us hold fast . . . without <qex>wavering</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. x. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In feeble hearts, propense enough before⟦br⟧
To <qex>waver</qex>, or fall <qex>off and join with idols</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reel; totter; vacillate. See
<er>Fluctuate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Waver
<hw>Wa"ver</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Wave</er>, or
<er>Waver</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>A sapling left standing in a
fallen wood.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waverer</ent>⟦br⟧
